    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nI'm trying to edit a file that might or might not be opened as a buffer, using `nvim_buf_set_lines`. Unfortunately, unless the buffer is visible in a window, it seems that `nvim_buf_set_lines` will only set the first line, instead of the range provided.\r\nThis might be related to [#8659](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/8659), although the test circumstances are slightly different.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n`printf \"a\\nb\\nc\" > testfile`\r\n`nvim --clean`\r\n`:lua vim.api.nvim_buf_set_lines(vim.fn.bufnr(\"testfile\", true), 0, 4, false, {})`\r\n`:e testfile` - You will see that only the first line was cleared\r\n\r\n\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n`nvim_buf_set_lines` should set the lines specified in the range even for buffers that are not opened in a window.\r\nThe command above should've cleared the whole file.\r\n\n\n### Neovim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.8.3\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nN/A - Lua API\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nArtix Linux 6.1.12\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nAlacritty 0.11.0\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nalacritty\n\n### Installation\n\nPacman",
    "closed_at": "2023-10-29T07:44:54Z",
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Specifically this looks related to the `create` parameter of bufnr: \r\n\r\n    bufnr([{buf} [, {create}]]) \r\n\r\nThere might be an order-of-operations issue, but probably same general issue as https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/8659 : `nvim_buf_set_lines` and similar APIs should probably actively load buffers (or at least raise an error) if needed.",
